{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":25667,"record_hash":"sha256:1317fb67a1acfd4b2e57f3d2bd6124a40a878ef4452a47f03d1f6cd78b32468a","timestamp":"2026-05-11T10:09:22.788Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"They are not a correctness problem, but they are a design pressure signal.\n\nThe biggest individual stored records were mostly:\n- `compacted` records around `50 KB` to `108 KB`\n- `function_call_output` records around `40 KB+`\n- `exec_command_end` records around `12 KB`\n\nBecause GitMeta now stores large list entries as Git blobs, those huge rows are mostly not huge SQLite rows anymore. SQLite usually stores only a 40-byte object id for them. So they are not causing the old “SQLite explodes to 104 MB” problem in the same way.\n\nThe real question is whether they are useful enough to keep. Some are probably valuable:\n- `function_call_output` and `exec_command_end` may contain exactly what happened during the agent session.\n- `user_message` and `agent_message` are important for handoff/review.\n\nSome are more questionable:\n- `compacted` can duplicate/summarize large prior context.\n- `session_meta` included large `base_instructions` and `dynamic_tools`.\n- `turn_context` included large developer/user instruction blobs.\n- `token_count` seems low-value for the two future use cases.\n\nSo: not an urgent storage bug, but I would consider a small “event usefulness” filter soon. The POC can keep full provenance for now, but if we want this to scale gracefully, skipping or slimming low-signal events like `token_count`, maybe `session_meta.base_instructions`, `turn_context.developer_instructions`, and huge `compacted.replacement_history` would be the next sane lever.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T10:09:22.788Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}